post_text:
Online registration is now open for Returning students for the 2020-2021 school year at https://registration.powerschool.com/family/gosnap.aspx?action=24001&culture=en. It is required that you sign certain forms in order to pick up your child's chromebook or ipad; these forms are included as part of the online system.

You will need a "snapcode" for each child to complete the registration. If the school has a parent email address on file, you should have received an email with directions and the snapcode at that email address. If you have not received this email, call your child's school or go to the school to pick up the information.

Parents/guardians that used the registration system to complete online paperwork last summer already have an account. You can use the "Forgot password?" link if you can't remember your password or call the school for assistance in resetting it.

Hi Swain family, due to the Labor Day Holiday this week, we will have students on campus Wednesday, we will not be able to do a bus meal delivery this week. Instead, we are offering a drive through meal pick up on Wednesday at the Middle School Cafeteria from 12:30-2:30 pm. We will be providing 5 days of meals for any child 18 years old or under. Parents or guardians may pick up meals or you may send a friend or neighbor to pick up the meals if you are unavailable during this timeframe. To ensure that no child gets more than one 5 day meal pack we will be asking for the names of the children you are picking meals up for. We encourage all families to take advantage of this, you do not need to be enrolled in SCS to participate.
Call 828-488-3129 ext. 5139 or email jbrown@swainmail.org with questions.

post_text:
This is a message from The Swain County School Nutrition Program to let you know that all children in Swain County will receive school meals for FREE through August 31st. For children that are remote learning, we will offer a bus delivery on Wednesdays, and pick up options, please stay tuned for more info on that in the future. Starting September 1st, students will be charged for meals according to their free or paid meal status so please make sure you fill out the online application at www.lunchapplication.com. Students who qualify for reduced meals will get meals for free this year due to special funding made available. We encourage all students to fill out the meal application including remote learning students. Swain West Students and those who automatically get benefits due to food stamp enrollment do not have to fill out the application.
Please call the School Nutrition Office at 828-488-3129 ext. 5139 with questions.

post_text: Several questions have been asked about IEPs and services while schools are operating under plans B and C. Your child's special education teacher will be in contact with you in the upcoming weeks to create an individual remote learning contingency plan (RLCP) to address your child's needs for Plan B and/or Plan C. The plan will address your child's learning needs, modifications and accommodations for remote learning, and a plan for delivering related services if applicable. The RLCP will become part of the IEP, so an IEP meeting or IEP addendum will need to be held. You will have the option to participate in a face to face meeting (with appropriate social distancing and cloth face coverings), or a virtual meeting via phone conference or Google Meet.

post_text: Today is the last day for meal delivery by bus. We will continue to have pick up meals available from our cafeterias and will be available to do a limited number of deliveries to the community. If you can not get to the cafeteria and need a delivery, please call 828-488-3129 ext. 5126. Also, Swain Middle School Cafeteria will be closed next week, July 20th - 24th and will reopen Monday July 27th. East and West Elementary Cafeterias will be open next week. Please let us know if you have questions, call 828-488-3129 ext.5126 or email Jennifer Brown at jbrown@swainmail.org

post_text:
Swain County Schools is fully prepared to move forward, after Governor Cooper’s announcement, in Plan B. We have spent many hours preparing procedures for keeping our staff and students safe, knowing that regardless of the Governor’s decision those plans would prove to be a vital part. Now we will begin framing how we will proceed as well as what school will look like for our students and community in August.

It is vital that we work together in moving forward. As we begin to finalize our plans we will be reaching out to you for your assistance. Additional information will be coming on our social media feeds as well as the Maroon Devil Network.

post_text: Important information about reopening schools in NC.
text: Important information about reopening schools in NC.

post_text:
Swain West and East Elementary Schools invite you to come to the schools to turn your Kindergarten student’s paperwork in for the upcoming 2020-21 school year. Someone will call you to set up an appointment time, if you have registered your child. We are asking that you remain in your car and someone will come to help retrieve the documents and make copies. The following documents are required for your new student.

Birth certificate
Proof of residency
EBCI card
Physical ( we will have a form to give you)
Copy of immunization records
Custody papers if applicable
If you have not registered your child for Kindergarten, please call or come by the school for that paperwork.

WEST Wednesday, June 24. Phone number is 488-2119
EAST Thursday, June 25. Phone number is 488-0939

Swain County School Nutrition Program will have the following bus delivery schedule for the Memorial Day Weekend:
Buses will deliver meals today for today and tomorrow, and deliver tomorrow for Saturday, Sunday and Monday. You may also pick up weekend meals from the cafeterias today or tomorrow. Our cafeterias will be closed on Monday, May 25th and no deliveries will be made.
Thank you!

Online Bright Adventures Pre-K Registration for the 2020-2021 School Year is available NOW!

To enroll for the upcoming school year, preschoolers must be 4 years old on or before August 31st, 2020. Go to https://registration.powerschool.com/family/gosnap.aspx?action=23034&culture=en to complete the initial registration form; even if you have completed the original paper application earlier this year. The system does require an email address. Parents/guardians that used the registration system to complete online paperwork last summer for other Swain County students already have an account. You can use the "Forgot password?" if you cannot remember the password. Please direct questions about Bright Adventures enrollment to either Maxine Largent or Trishia Chapman at 488-1494.

post_text: This is an important message regarding free and reduced-price school meals, household applications, and P-EBT benefits. If you have a student currently enrolled in Swain County Public Schools and have had a change in income due to COVID-19, which may make you eligible for free or reduced-price school meals, please submit a new application at www.lunchapplication.com or contact the School Nutrition Department at 828-488-3129 ext. 5126 or 5139 for a paper application or if you have questions. Students enrolled at West Swain Elementary School (because it is a CEP school) or those currently receiving FNS (Food Stamp) benefits do not have to submit an application to receive P-EBT benefits.

post_text:
The Swain County School Nutrition Program will not be operating on the next three Fridays due to scheduled annual leave days. The school buses will be delivering extra meals on Wednesday and Thursday to make up for the Friday we are closed each week and for the weekend. You may also pick up extra meals from the cafeterias for these days. Please remember to refrigerate food that is not eaten within 2 hours of receiving. Also, please try to send out older children or adults for bus pick up and stand back from the bus and let drivers direct you on how to receive the meal so that we may maintain social distancing and keep our bus drivers and community safe.
You may call the school nutrition office at 828-488-3129 ext. 5126 or 5139 if you have any questions.

post_text: The Swain County Board of Education will be holding a special called meeting on Thursday, April 2,2020 in the Swain County Administration Building, 50 Main Street, 3rd Floor Auditorium, Bryson City, NC 28713. The meeting will begin at 5:30. The meeting will be broadcast on the school system youtube link at Maroon Devil Network https://youtu.be/7Doo40q_jF0. The purpose of the meeting will be to discuss calendar change, the budget appropriation request for the Swain County Commissioners, and provide updates on the school system closure. You can leave public comments or questions using the google form found at https://forms.gle/YjSXHSs8HC7rJCLh9. Appropriate social distancing and mass gathering limits will be observed.

The Swain County Board of Education will be holding a special called meeting on Thursday, April 2,2020 in the Swain County Administration Building, 50 Main Street, 3rd Floor Auditorium, Bryson City, NC 28713. The meeting will begin at 5:30. The meeting will be broadcast on the school system youtube link at Maroon Devil Network https://youtu.be/7Doo40q_jF0. The purpose of the meeting will be to discuss calendar change, the budget appropriation request for the Swain County Commissioners, and provide updates on the school system closure. You can leave public comments or questions using the google form found at https://forms.gle/YjSXHSs8HC7rJCLh9. Appropriate social distancing and mass gathering limits will be observed.

post_text:
School bus drivers will be running their regular school routes throughout Swain County today to deliver meals to children. They will make all regular stops to see if there are children that need meals. All kids will receive the meals for free. If there are other children at the homes the buses stop at, they may receive a meal too (they do not have to be enrolled in Swain County Schools to receive free meals).

The buses will be on routes between 10am and 12pm. The bus driver will stop at each bus stop, blow the horn and wait several minutes to see if someone comes out to pick up meals. Please send adults or older children out if possible to pick up the meals. Meals will still be available at school cafeterias to eat onsite or for pick up from 7:20am-2pm.

Swain County Schools cafeterias (excluding the high school) will be open for breakfast and lunch from 7:30am-2pm Mon-Fri for the next 2 weeks while schools are closed.
Any child 18 years old or younger is eligible to receive free meals at any of these sites (students do not have to be enrolled in Swain County Schools). Parents or other community members may pick up meals and deliver them to children in the community. We are working on other delivery methods at this time, so stay tuned for further updates.

In accordance with Governor Cooper’s Executive Order 117, Swain County Schools will be closed to students, beginning tomorrow March 16 and going through Friday March 27th. With this in mind Tomorrow Monday March 16th will be a Mandatory Teacher Workday for faculty and staff. No students will be allowed, including faculty and staff children. Faculty and staff should check with your building principal about meeting times during the day tomorrow.
Swain County Schools Food Services will provide free lunch and dinner tomorrow, if any parent would like to take advantage of the meals – East and West from 11-3, lunch and dinner from 11-7 at the Middle School. More food service opportunities will be available in the coming days, please stay tuned to all of our social media, as well as media outlets and website for more information.

post_text: Benjamin Cutler, Swain High English and creative writing teacher, has just been awarded first place in the North Carolina Poetry Society's 2020 American Heritage Poetry Contest for his poem, "A Fall Language." This award includes a cash prize and publication of the award-winning poem in the NCPS awards anthology, Pinesong. A muli-award-winning poet, Benjamin Cutler's poems have appeared in numerous literary magazines and publications, and he is the author of the full-length book of poetry, The Geese Who Might be Gods (Main Street Rag 2019).

post_text: 🎙 Students at Swain County High School will be hosting an Earth Day event on Saturday, April 25th from 11:00 am-2:00 pm in the high school gymnasium. The event is open to the public and free of charge with activities for all ages, including a one-hour wildlife presentation featuring live animals from the Balsam Mountain Trust. This wildlife program is sponsored by Mountain Wildlife Outreach with funds generated by the annual “Mountain Wildlife Days” event, which is held every July at the Sapphire Valley Resort in Cashiers. Other activities will include presentations by students and tables with information and activities by various local environmental and conservation organizations, including Highlands Biological Station, Mainspring Conservation Trust, and others. If you are interested in having a table to showcase your art, photographs, crafts, or ways you sustain our planet contact us at Swain High 488-2152 (ask for science faculty). Please join us for a fun event for all ages!

As students and staff exited the building, dust from the grinding lingered in the air causing the full evacuation. Swain County Fire Department cleared the building and determined there was no fire.

All students and staff are safe and have returned to school.

post_text:
Forecasts are calling for more saturating rainfall over the next week, with significant amounts falling on Monday and Tuesday. We are in contact with Swain County Emergency Services as well as the Department of Transportation, and in concert with them continually monitoring the situation. Please keep in mind that changes in our weather can occur quickly and many times with no warning.

We ask that you keep these circumstances in mind as we move forward this week. Our continuing pledge to our community is to always act with the utmost safety of our students and staff in mind. As situations change and arise Swain County Schools may have to dismiss and send students and staff home in a faster timeline than normal, which in turn would mean shorter notification times for our community. We ask for your understanding and patience as we move forward this week.

And as always Thank You for being a part of our Swain Family.

post_text:
🎙Swain County Schools Food and Nutrition Director Jennifer Brown has been named a NC Child Hunger Hero Award winner by the No Kid Hungry NC organization. The No Kid Hungry NC organization sponsors the awards across the state to give recognition to everyday heroes who make healthy meals possible for kids. Ms Brown is the driving force behind Swain County programs such as Summer Lunch, Grab and Go Breakfasts as well as finding ways to expand the Free Breakfast Program to all students.
Ms Brown will be recognized at the NC Child Hunger Leaders Conference on Wednesday, February 19, 2020, which will be held in Chapel Hill. Along with other winners from across the state Ms Brown will be celebrated on the "Wall of Fame" both at the conference and on the NoKidHungryNC.org website.

🔴THIS IS RESILIENCE WEEK (& ACEs Awareness) in North Carolina!
http://resilienceweek.co/

Watch the Resilience Movie on PBS Stations November 19 at 8pm to learn more about how to:

-Build the awareness of ACEs.
-Increase knowledge of trauma informed education.
-Share resources for building greater resilience.
-Amplify support for ongoing action and advocacy
in areas of childhood trauma and toxic stress.
